post_text:
National Preparedness Month Theme of the Week: Prepare for Disasters

Limit the impacts that disasters have on you and your family. Know the risk of disasters in your area and check your insurance coverage. Learn how to make your home stronger in the face of storms and other common hazards and act fast if you receive a local warning or alert.

Know what disasters and hazards could affect your area, how to get emergency alerts, and where you would go if you and your family need to evacuate. Make sure your family has a plan and practices it often.

Make sure to check local Cities and County agency Emergency Alert Systems and sign up for alerts. Also be sure to search for these alerts on all Social Media sites.
https://www.ready.gov/be-informed

https://www.ready.gov/alerts(Link for Wireless Emergency Alerts)

post_text:
The topic for Week 2 of National Preparedness Month is: Build A Kit

Gather supplies that will last for several days after a disaster for everyone living in your home. Don’t forget to consider the unique needs each person or pet may have in case you have to evacuate quickly. Update your kits and supplies based on recommendations by the Centers for Disease Control. After an emergency, you may need to survive on your own for several days. Being prepared means having your own food, water and other supplies to last for several days. A disaster supplies kit is a collection of basic items your household may need in the event of an emergency.

Please see the following web link to a list of supplies to help get you started.

https://www.ready.gov/kit
https://www.fema.gov/about/news-multimedia/app (download the FEMA App)
#BeReady

post_text:
September is designated as National Preparedness Month. Dealing with COVID-19 over the past 6 months has taught that being prepared for emergencies is of utmost importance. Emergencies are not just limited to pandemics, but can also include natural or man made disasters. Plans that are created can and should be designed to deal with many emergencies. Discuss and drill your plans with your family just like we do here in Prosper ISD with our Safety Drills.

Each week we will share resources that will enable you and your families to plan for the unexpected.

The Theme this year for National Preparedness Month is:

" Disasters Don’t Wait. Make Your Plan Today."

Week 1- Make a Plan-
Talk to your friends and family about how you will communicate before, during, and after a disaster. Make sure to update your plan based on the Centers for Disease Control recommendations due to the coronavirus.
https://www.ready.gov/plan (link to planning resources)

#BeReady
https://www.ready.gov/kids/be-ready-kids (share with your students: Ready kid)
https://www.ready.gov/september

post_text:
Hope Squad has organized "Be Kind" yellow T-Shirts as a symbol to simply be kind to one another, which is why you often see yellow shirts and apparel throughout our district on every Wednesday of each month. This stems from supporting the cause of suicide awareness and prevention. This year we have two shirt options for you to choose from and purchase through myschoolbucks for $10. Orders will be placed monthly and delivered to your child's campus. The first order will be placed September 1st.

Please log into your "MySchoolBucks" account to order your shirt. The shirts will delivered to your child's campus. https://www.myschoolbucks.com/ver2/getmain.action?clientKey=ZZH55P0BQF0824D&requestAction=home

Children's Health Stadium will be lit up yellow every Wednesday evening as a simple reminder for our community to exercise kindness. SO, if you find yourself driving around Prosper any Wednesday evening, run by the stadium to enjoy PISD's symbol for kindness.

post_text:
Prosper Family,

It has come to our attention that some students and/or parents are receiving emails made to look like it is coming from someone at Prosper ISD stating that the student will have to repeat this school year. We have been made aware of these emails and our technology team is working to trace the source. If you or your student(s) receive one of these emails, please immediately forward it upon receipt to homehelp@prosper-isd.net.

Additionally, there is a FAKE news article circulating on social media stating that the Governor, or other state leaders, has said that students will have to repeat this year. This is not a real news story and is untrue! No such mandate or order has been issued.

As always, please reach out if you have any questions.

The Prosper community is known for its charitable generosity. During this time of struggle for so many, our Seniors Citizens are often some of the hardest hit. See below for an opportunity to help our Senior neighbors.

If you can help, please bring donations to the front of Boyer Elementary School located at 1616 Montgomery Ln., Prosper, Tx. 75078 on Wednesday, March 25, 2020 from 10am - 2pm to benefit the Collin County Meals on Wheels.

Donations needed include: Adult pull-up diapers, toilet paper, bed pads, daily pads, wet wipes, toiletries, towels, kleenex, games/activities/puzzles, cans of soup, microwaveable meals, instant oatmeal, peanut butter crackers, fruit cups, fruit snacks, granola/protein bars, juice boxes, jello/pudding.

Some Seniors have pets so pet food and kitty litter are also good items to donate.

For more information, contact: Stephen Rapp 903-271-9774

post_text:
Reminder of Winter Weather Procedures:
In the event of winter weather, the decision to close schools or delay start times will be announced no later than 6am of the day in question. Parents and families can expect to receive notification of school closings/delayed start via email, text, social media, PISD website alerts, and/or Local Radio & Television Station Announcements.

We are happy to announce that Celebrate Calm - 10 Ways to Stop Defiance, Disrespect & Yelling Workshop is returning to Prosper ISD on October 22 for two free workshops.

Morning Session
Tuesday, October 22
9:00am – 11:00am
Prosper ISD Administration Building / 605 E. 7th St. / Prosper, TX 75078 (Room 108)
Registration required ONLY for the AM event as space is limited. Please register below: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/70A0C4CADAF22A5F49-celebrate1

Evening Session
Tuesday, October 22
6:30pm – 8:30pm
Prosper High School Auditorium / 301 Eagle Dr. / Prosper, TX 75078
No registration required for the evening event.

Kirk will demonstrate 10 ways to:
• Get your kids to listen the first time.
• Stop power struggles with toddlers and teens.
• Stop whining, tantrums and sibling fights.
• Get kids to do their chores without a fight.
• Create stress-free mornings, homework time and bedtime.

For more information: shorturl.at/drAPR

Date: October 4th
Times: 6-8 PM
Location: PISD Children's Health Stadium

Homecoming Parade - Float Registration
Due Date: October 1st
The PHS Homecoming Parade is a great community event that is fun for the whole family. If you would like to participate in this year's parade, you will need to complete and return a registration form no later than NOON on October 1st to the PHS front office or mail the form to Trisha Brown, 5445 Oak Bend Trail, Prosper, TX 75078.
Parade Registration Form https://buff.ly/2ltNA8s
General Parade Information https://buff.ly/2n0esgC
Parade Questions trishabrown@suddenlink.net
